const faqSchema = { '@context': 'https://schema.org', '@type': 'FAQPage', mainEntity: [
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is EGCG and why is it important?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Epigallocatechin gallate (EGCG) is the most abundant and biologically active catechin in green tea, comprising 50-80% of total catechin content. EGCG is a potent antioxidant that has been studied for its effects on metabolism, fat oxidation, cardiovascular health, and neuroprotection. A 2009 meta-analysis in the International Journal of Obesity analyzing 11 studies found that green tea catechins (primarily EGCG) significantly increased fat oxidation by 16% and energy expenditure by 4-5%. EGCG works by inhibiting catechol-O-methyltransferase (COMT), an enzyme that breaks down norepinephrine, thereby prolonging the thermogenic (calorie-burning) effects of this catecholamine.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How much green tea extract should I take daily?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Clinical studies showing metabolic benefits typically used 270-800mg of EGCG per day, equivalent to approximately 500-1,500mg of standardized green tea extract (typically standardized to 50% EGCG). Most green tea gummies provide 200-500mg of green tea extract per serving. For antioxidant and metabolic support, 300-500mg of extract (providing 150-250mg EGCG) daily is a reasonable target. The European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) has suggested a conservative upper limit of 800mg EGCG per day from supplements. It is important not to exceed this, as very high EGCG doses have been associated with rare cases of liver toxicity.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Do green tea gummies help with weight loss?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Green tea catechins (EGCG) can modestly support weight management as part of a comprehensive approach that includes diet and exercise. The 2009 meta-analysis found that green tea catechins increased fat oxidation by 16% and energy expenditure by about 80 calories per day — meaningful over time but not a dramatic standalone effect. A 2012 Cochrane review of 14 RCTs found that green tea produced a small but statistically significant weight loss of approximately 1.3kg compared to placebo over 12 weeks. Green tea is best understood as a metabolic support ingredient that enhances the results of diet and exercise, not a miracle weight loss supplement on its own.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Do green tea gummies contain caffeine?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Most green tea gummies contain some caffeine, though significantly less than a cup of green tea. A typical cup of green tea contains 25-50mg of caffeine. Green tea extract gummies generally contain 10-40mg of caffeine per serving depending on the extraction method and whether the product is decaffeinated. Some products use decaffeinated green tea extract, retaining the EGCG and catechins while removing most caffeine. If you are sensitive to caffeine, look for products labeled "decaffeinated" or "caffeine-free" green tea extract. Taking green tea gummies in the morning or early afternoon minimizes any sleep disruption.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Is green tea extract safe for the liver?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Green tea extract at recommended doses (fewer than 800mg EGCG per day) is generally safe for healthy adults. However, very high doses of EGCG — typically exceeding 800mg per day from concentrated supplements — have been associated with rare cases of hepatotoxicity (liver injury). The European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) reviewed the evidence in 2018 and confirmed that EGCG doses below 800mg/day from supplements showed no evidence of liver harm. To minimize risk: do not exceed recommended doses, take green tea extract with food (reduces peak EGCG levels), avoid combining with other hepatotoxic substances (excessive alcohol, acetaminophen), and discontinue use if you experience abdominal pain, dark urine, or jaundice.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Can I take green tea gummies on an empty stomach?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Taking green tea extract on an empty stomach increases both the absorption rate and peak blood levels of EGCG, which may enhance its metabolic effects but also increases the risk of nausea and, at high doses, potential liver stress. The EFSA recommends taking green tea extract supplements with food to moderate absorption and reduce the risk of adverse effects. If you experience nausea when taking green tea gummies, take them with or immediately after a meal. For most people, taking them with breakfast provides a good balance of absorption and tolerability.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is the difference between matcha and green tea extract?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Matcha is whole green tea leaves ground into a fine powder — you consume the entire leaf, including the fiber and chlorophyll. Green tea extract is a concentrated preparation that isolates and concentrates the catechins (especially EGCG) from green tea leaves. Gram for gram, green tea extract provides significantly more EGCG than matcha because it is concentrated. A typical green tea extract supplement provides 150-400mg of EGCG per serving, while a cup of matcha provides approximately 60-100mg of EGCG. However, matcha also provides L-theanine, chlorophyll, and fiber that extract may lack. For targeted EGCG supplementation, extract is more efficient; for whole-food nutrition, matcha is more complete.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Can I take green tea gummies with other supplements?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Green tea extract pairs well with most supplements but has a few interactions to note. It may enhance the effects of caffeine-containing supplements (increased jitteriness). EGCG can reduce iron absorption — take green tea gummies at least 2 hours apart from iron supplements. Green tea may interact with blood thinners (warfarin) by competing with vitamin K metabolism. It may also interact with beta-blockers and certain chemotherapy drugs. Green tea pairs positively with vitamin C (enhances catechin stability and absorption), turmeric (complementary antioxidant pathways), and CLA (complementary fat metabolism support). Consult your pharmacist if you take prescription medications.' } },
] };
