    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Green Tea Gummies</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What is EGCG and why is it important?</summary><p>EGCG is the primary bioactive catechin in green tea, responsible for its antioxidant, metabolic, and cardiovascular benefits. It inhibits COMT to prolong fat-burning norepinephrine signaling.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much green tea extract should I take daily?</summary><p>200-400mg of EGCG (from 400-800mg standardized extract). Stay below the EFSA-suggested 800mg EGCG/day limit from supplements.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do green tea gummies help with weight loss?</summary><p>Green tea increases fat oxidation by 16% and energy expenditure by ~80 cal/day. It supports weight management as part of a comprehensive approach, not as a standalone solution.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do green tea gummies contain caffeine?</summary><p>Most contain 10-40mg per serving. Decaffeinated options are available that retain EGCG while removing caffeine.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Is green tea extract safe for the liver?</summary><p>Safe below 800mg EGCG/day per EFSA guidelines. Take with food to reduce peak absorption. Avoid combining with excessive alcohol or acetaminophen.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take green tea gummies on an empty stomach?</summary><p>Taking with food is recommended to moderate absorption and reduce nausea risk. The EFSA specifically suggests food co-consumption.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What is the difference between matcha and green tea extract?</summary><p>Matcha is whole ground tea leaves. Extract is concentrated catechins. Extract provides more EGCG per mg; matcha provides additional L-theanine and chlorophyll.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take green tea gummies with other supplements?</summary><p>Pairs well with vitamin C and turmeric. Separate from iron supplements by 2 hours. Consult your pharmacist if taking blood thinners or beta-blockers.</p></details>

    <div class="warn-box"><span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span><p><strong>Important:</strong> Do not exceed 800mg EGCG per day from supplements (EFSA guideline). Take green tea gummies with food. EGCG may reduce iron absorption — separate from iron supplements by 2 hours. If you experience abdominal pain, dark urine, or jaundice, discontinue use and consult your physician. Not recommended during pregnancy without physician approval.</p></div>

